AKURE – Justice Council of the Oil Producing Communities, a socio-political group, in Ondo State and the entire oil producing communities in the state have rejected the composition of the newly constituted Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC) Board. In statement entitled, “Composition of The Niger Delta Development Commission: A Subversion of The Act That Established The Commission,” signed by the spokesman of the group, Prince Segun Odolo, and made available to newsmen in Akure, the Ondo State capital, the group alleged that the Federal Government of violating the Act that established the Commission. Powered by RubiQube Ad Network The group claimed that the position of the Managing Director of the commission would have been occupied by Ondo State indigene if the Act had been upheld. The group alleged that since the establishment of the commission in year 2000, it had not been headed by indigene of the state despite the clause in the Act that states that the position of the Managing Director shall be rotational among the oil producing states. The statement reads inter alia, “The Justice Council of the Oil producing communities of Ondo State therefore frowned at and rejected in its entirety the composition of the Niger Delta Development Commission (NDDC) Board as announced on Tuesday, August 27, 2019. “We reject the purported composition because it violated the Act of NDDC and it is capable of causing disharmony among the member states of the commission.”